---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<BaseLayout title="Resources">
  <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto py-10 px-4 landing-content">

    <div class="mb-10">
      <h1>Resources</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Practical guidance for assessing each aspect of pilot readiness.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Business Impact -->
    <div class="mb-10" id="business-impact">
      <h2>Assessing business impact</h2>
      <p>TODO: How to evaluate whether improving this workflow would have meaningful business impact. Frameworks for estimating time saved, cost reduced, quality improved or risk lowered. How to distinguish "nice to have" from "critical."</p>
    </div>

    <div class="divider"></div>

    <!-- Frequency -->
    <div class="mb-10" id="frequency">
      <h2>Assessing workflow frequency</h2>
      <p>TODO: How to measure how often a workflow runs. Why frequency matters for automation ROI. How to account for workflows that are infrequent but high-impact vs frequent but low-stakes.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="divider"></div>

    <!-- Baseline Measurability -->
    <div class="mb-10" id="baseline-measurability">
      <h2>Establishing a baseline</h2>
      <p>TODO: How to measure current performance when no metrics exist. Practical approaches: manual time tracking for 2 weeks, pulling data from existing tools, asking the team to estimate cycle times. What "good enough" measurement looks like for a pilot. How to set up a baseline quickly without a big data project.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="divider"></div>

    <!-- Data Readiness -->
    <div class="mb-10" id="data-readiness">
      <h2>Assessing data readiness</h2>
      <p>TODO: What "good enough" data looks like for a pilot. Key questions to ask: Are the fields populated? Is it structured or unstructured? Can you access it programmatically? Are there privacy or compliance constraints? What to do when data quality is poor. The difference between "data is messy" and "data does not exist."</p>
    </div>

    <div class="divider"></div>

    <!-- Boundary Clarity -->
    <div class="mb-10" id="boundary-clarity">
      <h2>Figuring out what should stay with people</h2>
      <p>TODO: How to identify which parts of a workflow require human judgement, accountability or approval. Common patterns: customer-facing decisions, financial sign-off, legal or compliance review, creative judgement. The automation levels framework (link to Map page). Why unclear boundaries are a signal to defer, not push through.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="divider"></div>

    <!-- Pilotability -->
    <div class="mb-10" id="pilotability">
      <h2>Scoping a pilot</h2>
      <p>TODO: How to carve out a testable slice of a workflow. What makes a pilot scope too big or too small. How to handle dependencies and approvals. Setting up success criteria before you start. The 2-4 week rule of thumb and when to break it.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="divider"></div>

    <!-- AI Paradigms -->
    <div class="mb-10" id="ai-paradigms">
      <h2>AI paradigms and their risk profiles</h2>

      <p>
        These are fundamentally different technologies. An LLM can be asked to "follow rules" but that is not the same as a rules engine. A rules engine is deterministic: given the same input, it always produces the same output. An LLM following instructions is probabilistic: it might follow them correctly most of the time but it can hallucinate, misinterpret or drift. The choice of paradigm determines your risk profile, your boundary requirements and your testing strategy.
      </p>

      <p>TODO: For each paradigm below, add detailed sections covering:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>What it actually is (technically, in plain language)</li>
        <li>What it is NOT (common misconceptions)</li>
        <li>When to use it (concrete examples)</li>
        <li>When not to use it</li>
        <li>Risk profile and what can go wrong</li>
        <li>What boundaries you need</li>
        <li>How to test it before going live</li>
        <li>Real-world examples (good and bad)</li>
      </ul>

      <h3 id="paradigm-rules">Rules and automation</h3>
      <p>TODO: Deterministic logic. If X then Y. No model, no learning, no uncertainty. Spreadsheet formulas, workflow automation tools, business rules engines. Why this is the safest option for high autonomy. When people think they need AI but actually need rules. The difference between an LLM following instructions and a rules engine.</p>

      <h3 id="paradigm-ml">Machine learning (classification and prediction)</h3>
      <p>TODO: Trained models that learn patterns from historical data. How they work at a high level. Bias, data drift, retraining requirements. The black-box problem. When ML is the right choice vs when rules or LLMs are better. Examples: lead scoring, spam filtering, demand forecasting.</p>

      <h3 id="paradigm-llm-copilot">LLM as copilot</h3>
      <p>TODO: A language model that supports a human. The human drives, AI assists. Drafting, summarisation, explanation, brainstorming. Why the human-in-the-loop makes this lower risk. Hallucination is still a problem but the human catches it. When copilot mode is enough vs when you need more autonomy.</p>

      <h3 id="paradigm-llm-agent">LLM as agent</h3>
      <p>TODO: An LLM that takes actions autonomously. The human sets the goal, AI figures out the steps. Tool calling, API access, multi-step workflows. Why this is significantly higher risk than copilot mode. Compounding errors. Scope creep. The importance of strong boundaries and monitoring. When agent mode is justified vs when it is unnecessary risk.</p>

      <h3 id="paradigm-rag">RAG (retrieval-augmented generation)</h3>
      <p>TODO: An LLM that retrieves information from a knowledge base before generating a response. How it differs from a plain LLM (grounded in actual sources). The critical importance of source quality and access control. Chunking strategies and how they affect output quality. Why citation does not guarantee correctness. When RAG is the right choice for knowledge retrieval.</p>

      <h3 id="paradigm-hybrid">Hybrid (deterministic core + AI layer)</h3>
      <p>TODO: Systems where the critical logic is deterministic and AI handles the language-rich parts. The CFO reporting example: calculations are rules-based, narrative is LLM-generated. Why boundary enforcement between the two layers is architectural, not just policy. When hybrid is worth the complexity.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="divider"></div>

    <!-- Automation Levels -->
    <div class="mb-10" id="automation-levels">
      <h2>Automation levels (0-5)</h2>

      <p>Inspired by the SAE levels of driving automation. A reference framework for describing how much control AI has in a given context. Not currently used as a per-step classification in the guide but useful as a shared language.</p>

      <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin-top: 1rem;">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th style="padding: 0.5rem 1rem; text-align: left; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); font-size: 13px;">Level</th>
            <th style="padding: 0.5rem 1rem; text-align: left; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); font-size: 13px;">Name</th>
            <th style="padding: 0.5rem 1rem; text-align: left; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); font-size: 13px;">What it means</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td style="padding: 0.5rem 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); font-weight: 700; color: var(--purple);">0</td><td style="padding: 0.5rem 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); font-weight: 600;">Fully human</td><td style="padding: 0.5rem 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); color: var(--text-light);">People do everything. AI is not involved.</td></tr>
          <tr><td style="padding: 0.5rem 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); font-weight: 700; color: var(--purple);">1</td><td style="padding: 0.5rem 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); font-weight: 600;">AI-assisted</td><td style="padding: 0.5rem 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); color: var(--text-light);">Human drives. AI supports with suggestions, lookups or drafts.</td></tr>
          <tr><td style="padding: 0.5rem 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); font-weight: 700; color: var(--purple);">2</td><td style="padding: 0.5rem 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); font-weight: 600;">AI-led, human-supervised</td><td style="padding: 0.5rem 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); color: var(--text-light);">AI handles the task. A human reviews and approves before it goes anywhere.</td></tr>
          <tr><td style="padding: 0.5rem 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); font-weight: 700; color: var(--purple);">3</td><td style="padding: 0.5rem 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); font-weight: 600;">AI-led, human on standby</td><td style="padding: 0.5rem 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); color: var(--text-light);">AI handles it and only escalates when something looks wrong.</td></tr>
          <tr><td style="padding: 0.5rem 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); font-weight: 700; color: var(--purple);">4</td><td style="padding: 0.5rem 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); font-weight: 600;">Autonomous within boundaries</td><td style="padding: 0.5rem 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); color: var(--text-light);">AI runs independently within defined rules. Humans set the rules, not the actions.</td></tr>
          <tr><td style="padding: 0.5rem 1rem; font-weight: 700; color: var(--purple);">5</td><td style="padding: 0.5rem 1rem; font-weight: 600;">Fully autonomous</td><td style="padding: 0.5rem 1rem; color: var(--text-light);">AI handles everything, any conditions. Rare in practice and high risk.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <div class="divider"></div>

    <!-- Glossary -->
    <div class="mb-10" id="glossary">
      <h2>Glossary</h2>
      <p>TODO: Plain-language definitions of key terms used throughout the guide. Gate, baseline, boundary, pilot, qualification, readiness profile, automation level, deterministic vs generative, approval gate, etc.</p>
    </div>

  </div>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .landing-content .subtitle {
    color: var(--text-light);
    font-size: 15px;
  }
</style>
